<div class="header">
  <div class="header-content">
    <div class="tag">Compiled by Gemini 3.1</div>
    <h1>American Tower (AMT)<br/>Intrinsic Value</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">A transparent, two-stage discounted cash flow valuation of American Tower Corporation. Derived strictly from actual financials and math.</p>
    <p class="date">Updated March 18, 2026 · Data: FY2025</p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="container">
  <!-- ═══ THE VERDICT ═══ -->
  <div class="verdict-card">
    <div class="verdict-label">Estimated Intrinsic Value Per Share</div>
    <div class="verdict-price">${roundedIV.toFixed(2)}</div>
    <div class="verdict-vs">vs. market price of ${currentPrice.toFixed(2)} ({marginOfSafety !== null ? marginOfSafety.toFixed(1) : 'N/A'}%)</div>
    <div class="verdict-badge" style={`background: ${verdictColor}22; color: ${verdictColor}; border: 1px solid ${verdictColor}44;`}>
      {verdictText}
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ METHODOLOGY ═══ -->
  <h2>Methodology: Two-Stage DCF</h2>
  <p>We use a <strong>two-stage discounted cash flow (DCF)</strong> model to estimate the intrinsic value of American Tower.</p>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">1</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Base Cash Flow Adaptation (OCF over FCF)</h4>
      <p>American Tower is a Real Estate Investment Trust (REIT) characterized by massive, consistent capital expenditures required to build and maintain cell towers globally. Consequently, its Free Cash Flow (FCF) does not represent the true operating power of the core business before growth investments. Therefore, we adapt our methodology to use <strong>Operating Cash Flow (OCF)</strong> as the base proxy, which was <strong>${(ocf2025).toLocaleString()}M</strong> in FY2025.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">2</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Mathematical Projections (Phase 1 & 2)</h4>
      <p>We mathematically derive our growth rates directly from historical performance and explicitly provided constants. Phase 1 growth is calculated using the 4-year Compound Annual Growth Rate (CAGR) of OCF. The Terminal Growth rate is derived directly from the 10-Year Treasury yield (4.18%), scaled down to ensure long-term sustainability below the risk-free rate.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">3</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Discounting & Debt (Enterprise to Equity Value)</h4>
      <p>The discount rate (WACC) is derived mathematically by combining the 10Y Treasury yield with a premium scaled to the company's historical growth rate. We calculate Enterprise Value from the discounted cash flows, then subtract total debt (${totalDebt.toLocaleString()}M) and add cash equivalents (${cashAndInvestments.toLocaleString()}M) to arrive at the final Equity Value, divided by shares outstanding.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ THE ASSUMPTIONS ═══ -->
  <h2>The Three Derived Assumptions</h2>

  <div class="assumption-grid">
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Phase 1 CF Growth Rate</div>
      <div class="value">{(growthRatePhase1 * 100).toFixed(1)}%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        Mathematically derived using the 4-year CAGR of Operating Cash Flow (from $4,820M in FY2021 to $5,464M in FY2025).
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Discount Rate (WACC)</div>
      <div class="value">{(discountRate * 100).toFixed(1)}%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        Derived entirely from the explicitly provided 10Y Treasury (4.18%) plus a premium calculated as a multiple of the company's historical growth rate.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Terminal Growth Rate</div>
      <div class="value">{(growthRateTerminal * 100).toFixed(1)}%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        Mathematically derived by scaling the 10Y Treasury yield (4.18% × 0.6) to represent sustainable long-term growth for a mature infrastructure company.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ CF PROJECTIONS TABLE ═══ -->
  <h2>Projected Cash Flows (Years 1-5)</h2>
  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Year</th>
          <th>OCF ($M)</th>
          <th>PV Factor</th>
          <th>Present Value ($M)</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Base (FY2025)</td>
          <td>${ocf2025.toLocaleString()}</td>
          <td>—</td>
          <td>—</td>
        </tr>
        {projectedCF.map(p => (
          <tr>
            <td>Year {p.year} ({2025 + p.year})</td>
            <td>${p.cf.toLocaleString()}</td>
            <td>{p.pvFactor !== null ? p.pvFactor.toFixed(4) : 'N/A'}</td>
            <td>${p.pvCF !== null ? p.pvCF.toLocaleString() : 'N/A'}</td>
          </tr>
        ))}
        <tr class="row-total">
          <td colspan="3">Sum of Phase 1 PV</td>
          <td class="highlight-cell">${pvPhase1.toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ TERMINAL VALUE ═══ -->
  <h3>Terminal Value</h3>
  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Component</th>
          <th>Value ($M)</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Year 6 Cash Flow (Year 5 × {(1 + growthRateTerminal).toFixed(4)})</td>
          <td>${Math.round(cfYear6).toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Terminal Value (CF₆ ÷ (WACC − Terminal Growth))</td>
          <td>${terminalValue.toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="row-total">
          <td>PV of Terminal Value</td>
          <td class="highlight-cell">${pvTerminalValue.toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ FINAL CALCULATION ═══ -->
  <h3>Final Valuation</h3>
  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Component</th>
          <th>Value ($M)</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>PV of Phase 1 Cash Flows</td>
          <td>${pvPhase1.toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>PV of Terminal Value</td>
          <td>${pvTerminalValue.toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>= Enterprise Value</td>
          <td>${enterpriseValue.toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>+ Net Cash (Cash − Debt)</td>
          <td>${netCash.toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>= Equity Value</td>
          <td>${equityValue.toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>÷ Shares Outstanding</td>
          <td>{sharesOutstanding !== null ? sharesOutstanding.toLocaleString() : 'N/A'}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="row-total">
          <td>Intrinsic Value Per Share</td>
          <td class="highlight-cell">${roundedIV.toFixed(2)}</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ SENSITIVITY ANALYSIS ═══ -->
  <h2>Sensitivity Analysis</h2>
  <p>How does the intrinsic value change if we tweak the derived growth rates and discount rates? Find the combination you believe in.</p>

  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table class="sensitivity-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Discount Rate ↓ / Growth →</th>
          {sensitivityGrowth.map(g => (
            <th class={g === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>{(g * 100).toFixed(1)}%</th>
          ))}
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {sensitivityTable.map(row => (
          <tr>
            <td>{(row.dr * 100).toFixed(1)}%</td>
            {row.values.map((v, i) => (
              <td class={row.dr === discountRate && sensitivityGrowth[i] === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>
                ${v}
              </td>
            ))}
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ RISKS ═══ -->
  <h2>Risks & Limitations</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Interest Rates:</strong> REITs like AMT are highly sensitive to interest rates. A significant spike in the 10Y Treasury above 4.18% would increase the discount rate and compress the intrinsic value.</li>
    <li><strong>Debt Load:</strong> AMT carries significant debt (${(totalDebt / 1000).toFixed(1)}B). While typical for REITs, rising refinancing costs could eat into Operating Cash Flow.</li>
    <li><strong>Tenant Consolidation:</strong> The telecom industry is highly concentrated. Mergers among major carriers (e.g., T-Mobile/Sprint in the past) can lead to tower decommissioning and reduced revenue.</li>
    <li><strong>International Exposure:</strong> AMT has significant operations in emerging markets, exposing cash flows to currency volatility and political risk.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use Operating Cash Flow instead of Free Cash Flow?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">American Tower is a Real Estate Investment Trust (REIT) characterized by massive capital expenditures (CapEx) to build and acquire cell towers. If we deduct all CapEx, the resulting Free Cash Flow is highly volatile and underestimates the cash-generating power of the existing tower assets. Using Operating Cash Flow provides a clearer view of the core business profitability before aggressive reinvestment.</div>
    </details>
